text: 100%. And you hit exactly on the pivot of not only what we're focused on now, but that we started seeing with this first big institutional investor. And it was simply that back in 2011, there just weren't as many smart pay ETFs. There was maybe 10 or a dozen value ETFs. And now there's several dozen. And there's a lot of different flavors. I think actually Two Sigma had a good research piece where they evaluated different specifications of value, different weighting schemes, and just simply showed the disparity in any given year, depending on how you identified value. And so one of the early conversations we had with this big institutional investor is, we were using a very liquid off-the-shelf value ETF. And we said, listen, because it's liquid, and it's cheap and transparent, we have confidence, especially its size. The last thing we wanted to run into was... Trying to become the biggest weight in a smaller value ETF where we had to go to the APs and try and get creates and things like that. So we opted for liquidity above all else. But we said to them, we could synthetically replicate a more sophisticated or a different specification of value, depending on your guys' preference or our thoughts. And ultimately, we didn't end up going that route. But I actually think it's the highest and best use of that implementation is exactly as... As you've identified. There's two layers to it. The replication methodologies is really a good default asset allocation scheme, let's say. And then depending on investor preferences, you can manufacture better or smarter exposures than is available on the off-the-shelf smart beta ETF landscape to have, as you said, a smarter beta clone portfolio.
